{"questionId":"32524681","questionHtml":"<p>The following table shows the probability distribution of a discrete random variable&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>X</mi></math>, where&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>a</mi><mo>,</mo><mo>&nbsp;</mo><mi>k</mi><mo>∈</mo><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">ℝ</mi><mo>+</mo></msup></math>.</p>\n<p style=\"text-align:center;\"><img src=\"__IMG__/df77a1e29d0ac31383c26617f633acb5da7da519.png\"></p>\n<p>Given that&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">E</mi><mfenced><mi>X</mi></mfenced><mo>=</mo><mn>2</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>6</mn></math>, find the value of&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>a</mi></math>.</p>","markschemeHtml":"<p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">E</mi><mfenced><mi>X</mi></mfenced><mo>=</mo><mi>k</mi><mo>+</mo><mn>2</mn><msup><mi>k</mi><mn>2</mn></msup><mo>+</mo><mn>3</mn><mi>a</mi><mo>+</mo><mn>4</mn><msup><mi>k</mi><mn>3</mn></msup><mo>=</mo><mn>2</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>6</mn></math>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;<em><strong> (A1)</strong></em></p>\n<p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>k</mi><mo>+</mo><msup><mi>k</mi><mn>2</mn></msup><mo>+</mo><mi>a</mi><mo>+</mo><msup><mi>k</mi><mn>3</mn></msup><mo>=</mo><mn>1</mn></math>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; <em><strong>(A1)</strong></em></p>\n<p><strong>Note: </strong>The first two<em><strong> A </strong></em>marks are independent of each other.</p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p><strong>EITHER</strong>&nbsp; (finding intersections of functions)</p>\n<p>attempt to make&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>a</mi></math> the subject in both of their equations&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; <em><strong>(M1)</strong></em></p>\n<p><em><strong><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>a</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>1</mn><mo>-</mo><mi>k</mi><mo>-</mo><msup><mi>k</mi><mn>2</mn></msup><mo>-</mo><msup><mi>k</mi><mn>3</mn></msup></math>&nbsp;</strong></em>and<em><strong>&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>a</mi><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mn>3</mn></mfrac><mfenced><mrow><mn>2</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>6</mn><mo>-</mo><mi>k</mi><mo>-</mo><mn>2</mn><msup><mi>k</mi><mn>2</mn></msup><mo>-</mo><mn>4</mn><msup><mi>k</mi><mn>3</mn></msup></mrow></mfenced></math></strong></em></p>\n<p>use of graph or table to attempt to find intersection&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; <em><strong>(M1)</strong></em></p>\n<p><strong>OR&nbsp; </strong>(solving algebraically)</p>\n<p>attempt to solve their equations algebraically to find a cubic in&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>k</mi></math>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;<em><strong>(M1)</strong></em></p>\n<p><em><strong><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msup><mi>k</mi><mn>3</mn></msup><mo>-</mo><msup><mi>k</mi><mn>2</mn></msup><mo>-</mo><mn>2</mn><mi>k</mi><mo>+</mo><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>4</mn><mo>=</mo><mn>0</mn></math>&nbsp;</strong></em>OR&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>3</mn><mfenced><mrow><mn>1</mn><mo>-</mo><mi>k</mi><mo>-</mo><msup><mi>k</mi><mn>2</mn></msup><mo>-</mo><msup><mi>k</mi><mn>3</mn></msup></mrow></mfenced><mo>=</mo><mn>2</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>6</mn><mo>-</mo><mi>k</mi><mo>-</mo><mn>2</mn><msup><mi>k</mi><mn>2</mn></msup><mo>-</mo><mn>4</mn><msup><mi>k</mi><mn>3</mn></msup></math>&nbsp;(or equivalent)</p>\n<p>attempt to solve their cubic in <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>k</mi></math>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; <strong><em>(M1)</em></strong></p>\n<p><strong>THEN</strong></p>\n<p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>a</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>773073</mn><mo>⋯</mo></math>&nbsp;OR&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>k</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>185928</mn><mo>…</mo></math></p>\n<p>(Other solutions to the cubic are:&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>k</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>1</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>92921</mn><mo>…</mo><mo>,</mo></math>&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>k</mi><mo>=</mo><mo>-</mo><mn>1</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>11514</mn><mo>…</mo><mo>)</mo></math></p>\n<p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>a</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>773</mn></math>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;<em><strong> &nbsp; A1</strong></em></p>\n<p style=\"text-align:right;\"><em><strong>[5 marks]</strong></em></p>","meta":{"questionId":"32524681","referenceCode":"23N.2.SL.TZ1.6","subjectId":"50-dp-mathematics-analysis-and-approaches","title":"The following table shows the probability distribution of a discrete random variable X, where a, k∈ℝ+. Given that EX=2.6, find the value of a.","paper":"2","level":"SL","questionNumber":"6","marksAvailable":"[Maximum mark: 5]","breadcrumbLabels":["Topic 2—Functions","Topic 4—Statistics and probability","Topic 4—Statistics and probability","SL 4.7—Discrete random variables","Topic 2—Functions","SL 2.10—Solving equations graphically and analytically"],"memberSectionIds":[],"sectionOrders":{}}}